ğŸ” Overview

Retail businesses lose revenue due to poor inventory decisionsâ€”either stocking too little (lost sales) or stocking too much (holding and wastage costs).

This project is an end-to-end data science system that:
	â€¢	Forecasts product demand using machine learning
	â€¢	Converts predictions into actionable inventory recommendations
	â€¢	Estimates financial impact of inventory decisions
	â€¢	Provides a user-friendly web interface for non-technical users

The goal is decision support, not just prediction accuracy.

â¸»

ğŸ¯ Problem Statement

Most small and mid-size retailers rely on:
	â€¢	intuition
	â€¢	recent sales trends
	â€¢	simple heuristics

These methods ignore demand variability, seasonality, and uncertainty, leading to:
	â€¢	frequent stockouts
	â€¢	overstocking
	â€¢	avoidable financial loss

â¸»

ğŸ’¡ Solution

The system follows a business-driven ML pipeline:
	1.	Demand Forecasting (Regression)
	â€¢	Predicts future sales quantity per product
	â€¢	Implemented using XGBoost
	2.	Inventory Decision Logic
	â€¢	Converts predicted demand into recommended stock levels
	â€¢	Incorporates safety stock assumptions
	3.	Cost Simulation
	â€¢	Estimates financial impact of overstocking and understocking
	â€¢	Compares ML strategy vs a naive baseline
	4.	Web Application
	â€¢	CSV upload â†’ predictions â†’ inventory recommendations â†’ downloadable results

â¸»

ğŸ“Š Model Evaluation (Why â€œAccuracyâ€ Is Not Used)

This is a regression problem, not classification.
	â€¢	There are no â€œcorrect / incorrectâ€ labels
	â€¢	Therefore, accuracy is not a valid metric

Metrics Used
	â€¢	MAE (Mean Absolute Error)
	â€¢	RMSE (Root Mean Squared Error)
Interpretation:
The ML model reduces demand prediction error by nearly 50% compared to a naive baseline.

â¸»

ğŸ’° Business Impact

Beyond prediction metrics, the system evaluates real business outcomes.

ğŸ“‰ Result:

~62% reduction in inventory-related costs compared to a baseline strategy.

This demonstrates that the model improves decision quality, not just numeric accuracy.

